Someone came to fix the floor in my kitchen, so I'm going to pretend I still have a job and work from home while reviewing Too Hot to Handle.
If I can manage to open this cursed file. (Damn it, OneDrive.)
*pirate voice* I'm there.
And that's where it starts drilling really hard. Great!
His passive-aggressive way of cranking my air purifier all the way makes me uncomfortable, but it smells like sawdust, so it's justified even if it's an anti-mask. And besides, I really need to protect myself, don't I??
I really want to go back to bed, but I can't until he leaves.
The positive thing is, I've finished rereading chapter 4!
Chapter five is long, but there's a lot of suspense. Good work.
In the middle of doing some find-and-replace on ... ➡️ ellipsis character, and there are 54 in this chapter 😅
But anyway, I care about it. The most natural speeches are mostly broken, especially when people let themselves go with their emotions.
The craftsman is vacuuming, and with a bit of luck, he'll soon be done.
He's gone (as far as I can tell) to cut something. So I took a look to see where he was. It's nowhere near done :(
Less than 7 pages left on chapter five. It remains my favorite chapter, and it's quite well done. A few layout changes, and minor adjustments to switch to the active voice and improve conciseness. That said, I'd really like a break and a cup of tea, but the guy is still messing around in my kitchen.
He just started vacuuming again. I hope that's a good sign.
The craftsman is gone!
He told me he had given a quote for the entire floor, but the homeowners were cheap and only paid for the small damaged area near the door. It's clearly better.
The house is airing out, and my air purifier is running in the kitchen while I enjoy a cup of tea in the garden!
